INSERT INTO xword.words (word, word_len, definition, submitter) VALUES ("taco","4","A ___  is a traditional Mexican dish consisting of a small hand-sized corn or wheat tortilla topped with a filling. The tortilla is then folded around the filling and eaten by hand. A ___ can be made with a variety of fillings, including beef, pork, chicken, seafood, vegetables, and cheese, allowing great versatility and variety. They are often garnished with various condiments, such as salsa, guacamole, or sour cream, and vegetables, such as lettuce, onion, tomatoes, and chiles. ___s are a common form of antojitos, or Mexican street food, which have spread around the world.","wiki"),("meat","4","___ is animal flesh that is eaten as food. Humans have hunted and killed animals for ___ since prehistoric times. The advent of civilization allowed the domestication of animals such as chickens, sheep, rabbits, pigs and cattle. This eventually led to their use in ___ production on an industrial scale with the aid of slaughterhouses.","wiki"),("corn","4","In North America, a ___ tortilla or just tortilla .","wiki"),("masa","4","___  is a maize dough that comes from ground nixtamalized corn. It is used for making corn tortillas, gorditas, tamales, pupusas, and many other Latin American dishes. Its dried and powdered form is called ___ harina, ___ de harina, and sometimes Maseca,","wiki"),("sope","4","A ___  are also added to create different tastes and styles of ___s; they are roughly the size of a fist.","wiki"),("beer","4","___ in Mexico has a long history. While Mesoamerican cultures knew of fermented alcoholic beverages, including a corn ___, long before the Spanish conquest, European style ___ brewed with barley was introduced with the Spanish soon after Hernán Cortés’s arrival. Production of this ___ here was limited during the colonial period due to the lack of materials and severe restrictions and taxes placed on the product by Spanish authorities.","wiki"),("dosa","4","A ___ is a rice pancake, originating from South Asia, made from a fermented batter. It is somewhat similar to a crepe in appearance. Its main ingredients are rice and black gram, ground together in a fine, smooth batter with a dash of salt. ___s are a typical part of the Southern Indian and Sri Lankan Tamil diets, but the dish is now popular all over the Indian subcontinent. Traditionally, ___s are served hot along with sambar and chutney. They can be consumed with idli podi as well.","wiki"),("idli","4","___ has several variations, including rava ___, which is made from semolina. Regional variants include sanna of Konkan.","wiki"),("naan","4","The earliest appearance of '___' in English is from 1803 in a travelogue of William Tooke.","wiki"),("poha","4","Flattened rice is rice which is flattened into flat, light, dry flakes originating from the Indian subcontinent. Rice is parboiled before flattening so that it can be consumed with very little to no cooking. These flakes of rice swell when added to liquid, whether hot or cold, as they absorb water, milk or any other liquids. The thickness of the flakes varies between almost translucently thin  to nearly four times thinner than a normal rice grain. It is also called 'beaten rice', not to be confused with ___, a Central-West Indian dish prepared using this flattened rice as the key ingredient.","wiki"),("roti","4","___ ","wiki"),("food","4","Historically, humans secured ___ through two methods: hunting and gathering and agriculture, which gave modern humans a mainly omnivorous diet. Worldwide, humanity has created numerous cuisines and culinary arts, including a wide array of ingredients, herbs, spices, techniques, and dishes.","wiki"),("fish","4","Many species of ___ are consumed as food in virtually all regions around the world. ___ has been an important source of protein and other nutrients for humans throughout history.","wiki"),("deer","4","___ .","wiki"),("lamb","4","A sheep in its first year is a ___ and its meat is also ___. A sheep in its second year and its meat are hogget. Older sheep meat is mutton. Generally, 'hogget' and 'sheep meat' are not used by consumers outside New Zealand and Australia, only the industry.","wiki"),("troy","4","After the literary time of the poem, the city was des___ed when the Greeks pretended to leave after secreting a squad of soldiers in a gigantic wooden horse monument, which the Trojans brought inside the walls. In the dead of night they exited the horse and opened the gates to the Achaeans nearby. ___ was burned and the population slaughtered, although many had other fates.","wiki"),("pork","4","___ is eaten both freshly cooked and preserved. Curing extends the shelf life of the ___ products. Ham, smoked ___, gammon, bacon and sausage are examples of preserved ___. Charcuterie is the branch of cooking devoted to prepared meat products, many from ___.","wiki"),("hams","4","The preserving of pork leg as ham has a long history, with Cato the Elder writing about the 'salting of ___' in his De Agri Cultura tome around 160 BC.","wiki"),("dogs","4","Dog meat is the flesh and other edible parts derived from ___. Historically, human consumption of dog meat has been recorded in many parts of the world.","wiki"),("cats","4","Cat meat is meat prepared from domestic ___ for human consumption. Some countries eat cat meat regularly, whereas others have only consumed some cat meat in desperation during wartime or poverty.","wiki"),("kant","4","Immanuel ___ , and that intuition is therefore independent from objective reality.","wiki"),("cows","4","Most beef skeletal muscle meat can be used as is by merely cutting into certain parts, such as roasts, short ribs or steak  is called veal.","wiki"),("pigs","4","A pig is any of the animals in the genus Sus, within the even-toed ungulate family Suidae. ___ include domestic ___ and their ancestor, the common Eurasian wild boar , along with other species. ___, like all suids, are native to the Eurasian and African continents, ranging from Europe to Pacific islands. Suids other than the pig are the babirusa of Indonesia, the pygmy hog of Asia, the warthog of Africa, and another genus of ___ from Africa. The suids are a sister clade to peccaries.","wiki"),("zinc","4","___ is a chemical element with the symbol Zn and atomic number 30. ___ is a slightly brittle metal at room temperature and has a blue-silvery appearance when oxidation is removed. It is the first element in group 12 of the periodic table. In some respects, ___ is chemically similar to magnesium: both elements exhibit only one normal oxidation state .","wiki"),("iron","4","In its metallic state, ___ is rare in the Earth's crust, limited to deposition by meteorites. ___ ores, by contrast, are among the most abundant in the Earth's crust, although extracting usable metal from them requires kilns or furnaces capable of reaching 1,500 °C  higher than what is enough to smelt copper. Humans started to master that process in Eurasia only about 2000 BCE, and the use of ___ tools and weapons began to displace copper alloys, in some regions, only around 1200 BCE. That event is considered the transition from the Bronze Age to the ___ Age. In the modern world, ___ alloys, such as steel, inox, cast ___ and special steels are by far the most common industrial metals, because of their mechanical properties and low cost.","wiki"),("salt","4","___ is a mineral consisting primarily of sodium chloride  of solids per liter of sea water, a salinity of 3.5%.","wiki"),("tofu","4","___, also known as bean curd, is a food prepared by coagulating soy milk and then pressing the resulting curds into solid white blocks of varying softness; it can be silken, soft, firm, or extra firm. Beyond these broad categories, there are many varieties of ___. It has a subtle flavor, so it can be used in savory and sweet dishes. It is often seasoned or marinated to suit the dish and its flavors, and due to its spongy texture it absorbs flavors well.","wiki"),("wood"